Unity=E2=80=99s Strategy
----------------

That leads to the final piece of context that explains this move; from Mobi=
legamer.biz ( https://mobilegamer.biz/unity-is-offering-a-runtime-fee-waive=
r-if-you-switch-to-levelplay-as-it-tries-to-kill-applovin/ ) :

Unity is quietly offering developers a Runtime Fee waiver if they switch to=
 its LevelPlay mediation platform, we=E2=80=99re told. =E2=80=9CThey just w=
ant to kill AppLovin=E2=80=9D, said one developer. Studios currently using =
Unity=E2=80=99s LevelPlay mediation platform have already been offered a 10=
0% Runtime Fee waiver, sources have told us. Unity account managers are als=
o telling developers not using LevelPlay that if they switch over from main=
 rival AppLovin or any other UA platform they can then unlock a Runtime Fee=
 waiver of 80-100%.

This isn=E2=80=99t a shock; Unity=E2=80=99s blog post announcement ( https:=
//blog.unity.com/news/plan-pricing-and-packaging-updates ) included this pa=
ragraph:

Qualifying customers may be eligible for credits toward the Unity Runtime F=
ee based on the adoption of Unity services beyond the Editor, such as Unity=
 Gaming Services or Unity LevelPlay mediation for mobile ad-supported games=
.

In short, use Unity=E2=80=99s margin-driving services (Unity Gaming Service=
s is Unity=E2=80=99s cloud service for developers), or pay for the Unity en=
gine; simply paying a per-seat licensing fee, particularly in an environmen=
t with little growth and hiring freezes, would no longer be enough.

This isn=E2=80=99t, for the record, an absurd decision to make, particularl=
y in the post-ATT era. This is the reality of Apple=E2=80=99s handicapping =
of ad-supported business models: the only possible response for impacted co=
mpanies is to either consolidate their business into their own data siloes =
or start explicitly charging; Unity is doing both.

At the same time, this is a massive change for anyone who has built on Unit=
y=E2=80=99s platforms: entire companies and business models were predicated=
 on not having to pay Unity on an ongoing basis. Worse, while a share of re=
venue model like that employed by Unreal Engine would mean foregone revenue=
, Unity=E2=80=99s approach of charging for installs would mean guaranteed c=
osts that preceded monetization. This flies directly in the face of Unity=
=E2=80=99s traditional value proposition, which is that you can experiment =
and iterate endlessly until you find a formula that works; now the very act=
 of experimentation and iteration in public means risking huge fees (and th=
at=E2=80=99s before you consider issues like piracy, install-bombing, etc.)=
.

I suspect that the key factor driving Unity=E2=80=99s implementation was th=
e aforementioned logistics issue: because Unity serves the long tail it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t have or want to build the resources to sign a contract and aud=
it every company that uses its engine like Epic does; a programmatic soluti=
on was necessary. At the same time, forcing every Unity game to only use th=
e Unity ad network and in-app purchase capability, which would allow Unity =
to share in revenue upside programmatically, would be considered even more =
abusive than this pay-on-install model, which still lets you use the moneti=
zation service of your choice (the you-have-no-choice model is, of course, =
what Apple uses: the company=E2=80=99s argument is that forcing every app t=
o use its in-app purchase is a matter of efficiently collecting its commiss=
ion, which is true!).

Unfortunately for Unity, solipsism isn=E2=80=99t an excuse for a model that=
 could result in taking >100% of developer revenue ( https://twitter.com/so=
sowski/status/1702700787116265536 ) , give rise to fraud and abuse, and whi=
ch is effectively retroactive: four months warning for a business model cha=
nge that won=E2=80=99t just impact new games but also existing ones is trus=
t-obliterating. Worse, Unity previously promised it wouldn=E2=80=99t change=
 the terms of service on developers ( https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2023/0=
9/wait-is-unity-allowed-to-just-change-its-fee-structure-like-that/ ) ; tha=
t clause was quietly deleted earlier this year.

And yet, at the same time, no one is going to re-write a game on a new engi=
ne. Developers who have been using Unity for years will be loath to switch.=
 And, while there is that slim possibility that developers actually lose mo=
ney with this change, most games will still pay Unity less than they would =
have Epic with its 5% take rate. Maybe Unity will get away with it?

